<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 2:15<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I2561f160630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>2.</label.designator><headtext>Witnesses</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><prop.head toc-guid="I259d25a0630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.designator>C.</label.designator><headtext>Examination</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id71f05d4682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>2:15.</label.designator><headtext>Oath or affirmation</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>A witness must take an oath or affirmation before testifying. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0287018088" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-6-603" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Id37b36907fbf11ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 24-6-603(a)</cite.query> states:</paratext><display.quote><para><paratext><begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>Before testifying, every witness shall be required to declare that he or she will testify truthfully by oath or affirmation administered in a form calculated to awaken the witness&apos;s conscience and impress the witness&apos;s mind with the duty to do so.<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0001"/>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic19d95c07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">1</footnote.reference>]</paratext></para></display.quote><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018088" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST17-8-52" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Id37bd2d07fbf11ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 17-8-52(a)</cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic19d95c17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">2</footnote.reference>] sets out the oath for criminal cases. <eos/><bos/>In both civil and criminal proceedings, the witness has the option of affirming rather than swearing. <eos/><bos/>If the witness affirms, the words “So help you God” are omitted, and the word “affirm” substituted for “swear.” <eos/><bos/>If the witness swears, then the words “or affirm” are omitted.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018088" w-serial-number="1987009430" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id37ce4427fbf11ea988285db8533e975"><ital>State v. Williams</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic19dbcd07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">3</footnote.reference>] held that there must be strict compliance with the statutory oath and that the trial court properly dismissed perjury counts against a defendant who testified as a witness before the grand jury without having been given a proper oath.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The oath is normally administered by the clerk, but may be administered by an attorney.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic19dbcd17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">4</footnote.reference>] If it is discovered during a trial that a witness was not sworn prior to testifying, then he may be sworn and state that his previous testimony was true.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic19dbcd27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">5</footnote.reference>] However, if the fact that he was not sworn is discovered after the conclusion of the trial, then the issue may not be raised on appeal.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic19de3e07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">6</footnote.reference>] Lastly, if the witness proceeds to testify despite his refusal to <page no="17"/>give a proper oath, the issue may not be raised on appeal absent an objection at trial.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic19de3e17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">7</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="Ic19d95c07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>This is now consistent with <cite.query w-src-number="0287018088" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USFRER603" w-pub-number="1000607" ID="Id37b84b07fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Fed. R. Evid. 603</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic19d95c17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><begin.quote ID="QT_0002"/>“Do you solemnly swear or affirm that the evidence you shall give to the court and jury in the matter now pending before the court shall be the truth, the whole truth, and nothing but the truth? <eos/><bos/>So help you God.”<eos/><end.quote refid="QT_0002"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic19dbcd07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018088" w-serial-number="1987009430" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id37d0b527fbf11ea988285db8533e975">State v. Williams, 181 Ga. App. 204, 351 S.E.2d 727 (1986)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic19dbcd17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018088" w-serial-number="1881014671" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000359" ID="Id37da7917fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Thomas v. State, 67 Ga. 460, 1881 WL 3408 (1881)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018088" w-serial-number="1898010389" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="Id37da7957fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Sikes v. State, 105 Ga. 592, 31 S.E. 567 (1898)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic19dbcd27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018088" w-serial-number="1905012000" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="Id37e1cc27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Southern Ry. Co. v. Ellis, 123 Ga. 614, 51 S.E. 594 (1905)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic19de3e07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018088" w-serial-number="1948104245" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id37e91f27fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Neidlinger v. Mobley, 76 Ga. App. 599, 46 S.E.2d 747 (1948)</cite.query>.<eos/><page no="17"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic19de3e17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>7</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018088" w-serial-number="2037563368" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id37ee0127fbf11ea988285db8533e975">Bennett v. State, 334 Ga. App. 381, 779 S.E.2d 420 (2015)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 2:15<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
